Use conditional compilation or the `MAUI` platform-specific service pattern:

```csharp
// MauiProgram.cs
public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
{
    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

#if ANDROID
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Android.AndroidNotificationService>();
#elif IOS
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.iOS.IosNotificationService>();
#elif WINDOWS
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Windows.WindowsNotificationService>();
#endif

    return builder.Build();
}
```

Each implementation lives under its respective `Platforms/` folder (e.g., `Platforms/Android/AndroidNotificationService.cs`), which is already conditionally compiled per-platform by the SDK's default `ItemGroup` rules.

**Alternative (no `#if`):** Put partial classes or file-scoped registrations in platform folders and call a shared extension method:

```csharp
// Services/ServiceRegistration.cs (shared)
public static partial class ServiceRegistration
{
    public static partial IServiceCollection AddNotificationService(this IServiceCollection services);
}

// Platforms/Android/ServiceRegistration.cs
public static partial class ServiceRegistration
{
    public static partial IServiceCollection AddNotificationService(this IServiceCollection services)
        => services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, AndroidNotificationService>();
}
```

Then in `MauiProgram.cs`:
```csharp
builder.Services.AddNotificationService();
```

Both approaches are safe — the build only compiles platform-specific code for its target, so there's no risk of missing types at runtime.
